<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06116087 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06116087 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  SWIMMING; BICYCLE; RUNNING; SPORT; GUIDELINE  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  SOME KEY points in getting ready for a triathlon, taken from &quot;TriathlonFitness Training&quot; by Sharon Given Svensson and Tony Svensson:;    (box) It iscritical to listen to your body at all times. If you are tired, rest, don'ttrain. To decrease the risk of injury, develop and follow a hard/easyschedule. This means that you never train hard in the same sport on twoconsecutive days.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Venture  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  TRIATHLON POINTERS  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  See also related article on page 7C of this section.  </MEMO><TEXT>     (box) The most important skill to master in open water is swimmingstraight. There is no line on the bottom of a lake or ocean so you must learnhow to &quot;sight&quot; by raising your head out of the water.;    (box) For cycling,wear a helmet. To quote from famous U.S. cyclist John Howard, &quot;There are twokinds of cyclists: those that have crashed and those that will.&quot;;    (box) Thelong, slow distance (LSD) run develops endurance. Most people save the LSD runfor the weekend. It should be approximately twice as long as your averagerun.;    (box) The week before the race, lower the intensity of your training.Swim easy, spin (avoid using big gears) on the bike and do some short, briskruns. The purpose of this week's workouts is just to stay loose.  </TEXT><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910425  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Thursday  </DAY><MONTH>  April  </MONTH><PG.COL>  8C  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  213  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Thursday April 25, 199100116087,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>